$$ 0.31\mathrm{K}/\mathrm{W}{\mathrm{m}}^{-2}\times 2.3\mathrm{W}{\mathrm{m}}^{-2} $$
\end{document} is equal to 0.7 K (which is the same as 0.7 °C),9 quite close to the observed rise in GMSTglobal mean surface temperature (about 0.9 °C) over the course of the Anthropocene. As examined in detail in Chap. 2, the actual relationship between ΔTGMST anomaly and ΔRFradiative forcing requires a consideration of factors such as climate feedbackclimate feedback (i.e., enhancement or diminution of the RF ofradiative forcing climate imposed by humans due to changes in factors such as atmospheric humidity and cloudsclouds) as well as the transport of heat from the atmosphere to the world’s oceans, which specialists refer to as ocean heatocean heat export. It is likely, for instance, that positive feedback (enhancement) of the direct RF ofradiative forcing climate caused by humans is responsible for the difference between the expected (0.7 °C) and observed (0.9 °C) rise in GMSTglobal mean surface temperature over the course of the Anthropocene. Most importantly, the calculation conducted above reveals quantitative consistency between the observed and expected rise in global temperature over the course of the Anthropocene. This is a critically important first step in the attribution of global warmingglobal warming to humans.

We turn our attention to the scientific importance of the numerical estimates of the CH4methanesourcemethanesources and sinkmethanesinks strengths shown in Fig. 1.9. The globally averaged sink for CH4methane is 550 Tg per year. The mass of CH4methane in the atmosphere, at present,23 is about 5326 Tg. The atmospheric lifetime of CH4methane is given by:1.7τCH4=MassRemovalRate=5326Tg550Tgyear−1=9.7year\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
