$$ {\tau}_{CH4} = \frac{Mass}{Removal\  Rate} = \frac{5326\mathrm{Tg}}{550\mathrm{Tg}\ {\mathrm{year}}^{-1}} = 9.7\mathrm{year} $$
\end{document}On average, a molecule of CH4methane released to the atmosphere will persist for about a decade until it is removedmethanesinks by either a chemical reaction or a soil microbe. Prather et al. (2012) report a present-day CH4methane lifetime of 9.1 ± 0.9 years, consistent with our calculation above. Conversely, a lifetime of 12.4 years for CH4methane was used by IPCC (2013) in the calculation of GWPsglobal warming potential because it is thought that the release of a large pulse of CH4methane to the atmosphere will prolong the atmospheric lifetime, due to resulting changes in the chemical composition of the tropical tropospheretroposphere.

